    {
      "content": "Introduction to Service Fabric Health Monitoring",
      "pos": [
        26,
        74
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This article describes the Azure Service Fabric Health Monitoring model, including health entities, reporting and evaluation.",
      "pos": [
        92,
        217
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Introduction to Service Fabric Health Monitoring",
      "pos": [
        508,
        556
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Service Fabric introduces a health model that provides rich, flexible and extensible health evaluation and reporting.",
      "pos": [
        557,
        674
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This includes near real-time monitoring of the state of the cluster and of the services running in it.",
      "pos": [
        675,
        777
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You  can easily obtain the health information and take actions to correct potential issues before they cascade and cause massive outages.",
      "pos": [
        778,
        915
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The typical model is that services send reports based on their local view and the information is aggregated to provide an overall cluster level view.",
      "pos": [
        916,
        1065
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Service Fabric components use this health model to report their current state.",
      "pos": [
        1067,
        1145
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "And you can use the same mechanism to report health from your applications.",
      "pos": [
        1146,
        1221
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The quality and richness of health reporting specific to your custom conditions will determine how easily you will be able to detect and fix issues for your running application.",
      "pos": [
        1222,
        1399
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> We started the Health subsystem as a need for monitored upgrades.",
      "pos": [
        1403,
        1481
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Service Fabric provides monitored upgrades that know how to upgrade a cluster or an application with no down time, minimum to no user intervention and with full cluster and application availability.",
      "pos": [
        1482,
        1680
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To do this, the upgrade checks health based on configured upgrade policies and allows upgrade to proceed only when health respects desired thresholds.",
      "pos": [
        1681,
        1831
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Otherwise, the upgrade is either automatically rolled back or paused to give administrators a chance to fix the issues.",
      "pos": [
        1832,
        1951
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To learn more about application upgrades see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>this article<ept id=\"p1\">](service-fabric-application-upgrade.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        1952,
        2051
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Health Store",
      "pos": [
        2056,
        2068
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Health Store keeps health related information about entities in the cluster for easy retrieval and evaluation.",
      "pos": [
        2069,
        2183
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is implemented as a Service Fabric persisted stateful service to ensure high availability and scalability.",
      "pos": [
        2184,
        2293
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is part of the fabric:/System application and is available as soon as the cluster is up and running.",
      "pos": [
        2294,
        2397
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Health entities and hierarchy",
      "pos": [
        2402,
        2431
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The health entities are organized in a logical hierarchy that captures interactions and dependencies between different entities.",
      "pos": [
        2432,
        2560
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The entities and the hierarchy are automatically built by the Health Store based on reports received from the Service Fabric components.",
      "pos": [
        2561,
        2697
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The health entities mirror the Service Fabric entities (eg.",
      "pos": [
        2699,
        2758
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "health application entity matches an application instance deployed in the cluster, health node entity matches a Service Fabric cluster node).",
      "pos": [
        2759,
        2900
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The health hierarchy captures the interactions of the system entities and is the basis for advanced health evaluation.",
      "pos": [
        2901,
        3019
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can learn about the key Service Fabric concepts at <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Service Fabric technical overview<ept id=\"p1\">](service-fabric-technical-overview.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        3020,
        3149
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more on application, go to <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Service Fabric application model<ept id=\"p1\">](service-fabric-application-model.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        3150,
        3253
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The health entities and hierarchy allow for effective reporting, debugging and monitoring of the cluster and applications.",
      "pos": [
        3255,
        3377
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The health model allows an accurate, <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>granular<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> representation of the health of the many moving pieces in the cluster.",
      "pos": [
        3378,
        3498
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Health Entities.",
      "pos": [
        3502,
        3518
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The health entities, organized in an hierarchy based on parent-children relationships.",
      "pos": [
        3523,
        3609
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The health entities are:",
      "pos": [
        3695,
        3719
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Cluster<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        3723,
        3735
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Represents the health of a Service Fabric cluster.",
      "pos": [
        3736,
        3786
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cluster health reports describe conditions that affect the entire cluster and can't be narrowed down to one or more unhealthy children.",
      "pos": [
        3787,
        3922
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Example: split-brain of the cluster due to network partitioning or communication issues.",
      "pos": [
        3923,
        4011
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Node<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        4015,
        4024
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Represents the health of a Service Fabric node.",
      "pos": [
        4025,
        4072
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Node health reports describe conditions that affect the node functionality and typically affect all the deployed entities running on it.",
      "pos": [
        4073,
        4209
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Example: node is out of disk space (or other machine wide property such as memory, connections, etc.) or node is down.",
      "pos": [
        4210,
        4328
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The node entity is identified by the node name (string).",
      "pos": [
        4329,
        4385
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Application<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        4389,
        4405
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Represents the health of an application instance running in the cluster.",
      "pos": [
        4406,
        4478
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Application health reports describe conditions that affect the overall health of the application and can't be narrowed down to individual children (services or deployed applications).",
      "pos": [
        4479,
        4662
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Example: the end to end interaction between different services in the application.",
      "pos": [
        4663,
        4745
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The application entity is identified by the application name (Uri).",
      "pos": [
        4746,
        4813
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Service<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        4817,
        4829
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Represents the health of a service running in the cluster.",
      "pos": [
        4830,
        4888
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Service health reports describe conditions that affect the overall health of the service, and can't be narrowed down to a partition or a replica.",
      "pos": [
        4889,
        5034
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Example: a service configuration (such as port or external file share) that is causing issues for all partitions.",
      "pos": [
        5035,
        5148
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The service entity is identified by the service name (Uri).",
      "pos": [
        5149,
        5208
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Partition<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5212,
        5226
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Represents the health of a service partition.",
      "pos": [
        5227,
        5272
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Partition health reports describe conditions that affect the entire replica set.",
      "pos": [
        5273,
        5353
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Example: the number of replicas is below target count or partition is in quorum loss.",
      "pos": [
        5354,
        5439
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The partition entity is identified by the partition id (Guid).",
      "pos": [
        5440,
        5502
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Replica<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5506,
        5518
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Represents the health of a stateful service replica or a stateless service instance.",
      "pos": [
        5519,
        5603
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is the smallest unit watchdogs and system components can report on for an application.",
      "pos": [
        5604,
        5695
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Example: For stateful services, primary replica can report if it can't replicate operations to secondaries or replication is not proceeding at the expected pace.",
      "pos": [
        5696,
        5857
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A stateless instance can report if it is running out of resources or has connectivity issues.",
      "pos": [
        5858,
        5951
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The replica entity is identified by the partition id (Guid) and the replica or instance id (long).",
      "pos": [
        5952,
        6050
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>DeployedApplication<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        6054,
        6078
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Represents the health of an <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>application running on a node<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        6079,
        6139
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Deployed application health reports describe conditions specific to the application on the node that can't be narrowed down to service packages deployed on the same node.",
      "pos": [
        6140,
        6310
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Example: the application package can't be downloaded on that node or there is an issue setting up application security principals on the node.",
      "pos": [
        6311,
        6453
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The deployed application is identified by application name (Uri) and node name (string).",
      "pos": [
        6454,
        6542
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>DeployedServicePackage<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        6546,
        6573
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Represents the health of a service package of an application running in a node in the cluster.",
      "pos": [
        6574,
        6668
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It describes conditions specific to a service package that do not affect the other service packages on the same node for the same application.",
      "pos": [
        6669,
        6811
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Example: a code package in the service package cannot be started or configuration package cannot be read.",
      "pos": [
        6812,
        6917
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The deployed service package is identified by application name (Uri), node name (string) and service manifest name (string).",
      "pos": [
        6918,
        7042
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The granularity of the health model makes it easy to detect and correct issues.",
      "pos": [
        7044,
        7123
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, if a service is not responding, it is feasible to report that the application instance is unhealthy; however, it is not ideal because the issue might not be affecting all services within that application.",
      "pos": [
        7124,
        7341
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The report should be applied on the unhealthy service, or, if more information points to a specific child partition, on that partition.",
      "pos": [
        7342,
        7477
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The data will automatically surface through the hierarchy: an unhealthy partition will be made visible at service and application levels.",
      "pos": [
        7478,
        7615
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This will help pinpoint and resolve the root cause of the issues faster.",
      "pos": [
        7616,
        7688
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The health hierarchy is composed of parent-children relationships.",
      "pos": [
        7690,
        7756
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cluster is composed of nodes and applications; applications have services and deployed applications; deployed applications have deployed service packages.",
      "pos": [
        7757,
        7911
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Services have partitions, and each partition has one or more replicas.",
      "pos": [
        7912,
        7982
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is a special relationship between nodes and deployed entities.",
      "pos": [
        7983,
        8051
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If a node is unhealthy as reported by its authority System component (Failover Manager Service), it will affect the deployed applications, service packages and replicas deployed on it.",
      "pos": [
        8052,
        8236
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The health hierarchy represents the latest state of the system based on the latest health reports, which is almost real-time information.",
      "pos": [
        8238,
        8375
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Internal and external watchdogs can report on the same entities based on application specific logic or custom monitored conditions.",
      "pos": [
        8376,
        8507
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The user reports co-exist with the system reports.",
      "pos": [
        8508,
        8558
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Investing time on planning how to report and respond to health while designing the service makes large cloud services easier to debug, monitor, and subsequently operate.",
      "pos": [
        8560,
        8729
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Health states",
      "pos": [
        8734,
        8747
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Service Fabric uses three health states to describe whether an entity is healthy or not: Ok, Warning and Error.",
      "pos": [
        8748,
        8859
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Any report sent to the Health Store must specify one of these states.",
      "pos": [
        8860,
        8929
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The health evaluation result is one of these states.",
      "pos": [
        8930,
        8982
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The possible health states are:",
      "pos": [
        8984,
        9015
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Ok: The entity is healthy.",
      "pos": [
        9019,
        9045
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are no known issues reported on it or its children (when applicable).",
      "pos": [
        9046,
        9121
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Warning: The entity experiences some issues but it is not yet unhealthy (i.e., unexpected delay that it is not causing any functional issue).",
      "pos": [
        9125,
        9266
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In some cases, the warning condition may fix itself without any special intervention, and it is useful to provide visibility into what is going on.",
      "pos": [
        9267,
        9414
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In other cases, the Warning condition may degrade into a severe problem without user intervention.",
      "pos": [
        9415,
        9513
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Error: The entity is unhealthy.",
      "pos": [
        9517,
        9548
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Action should be taken to fix the state of the entity, as it can't function properly.",
      "pos": [
        9549,
        9634
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Unknown: The entity doesn't exist in the health store.",
      "pos": [
        9638,
        9692
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This result can be obtained from distributed queries like get the Service Fabric nodes or applications.",
      "pos": [
        9693,
        9796
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These queries merge results from multiple system components.",
      "pos": [
        9797,
        9857
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If another system component has an entity that has not reached the health store yet or that has been cleaned up from health store, the merged query will populate health result with 'Unknown' health state.",
      "pos": [
        9858,
        10062
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Health policies",
      "pos": [
        10067,
        10082
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Health Store applies health policies to determine whether an entity is healthy based on its reports and its children.",
      "pos": [
        10083,
        10204
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> The health policies can be specified in the cluster manifest (for cluster and node health evaluation) or the application manifest (for application evaluation and any of its children).",
      "pos": [
        10208,
        10404
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The health evaluation requests can also pass in custom health evaluation policies, which will only be used for that evaluation.",
      "pos": [
        10405,
        10532
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By default, Service Fabric applies strict rules (everything must be healthy) for the parent-children hierarchical relationship; as long as one of the children has one unhealthy event, the parent is considered unhealthy.",
      "pos": [
        10534,
        10753
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cluster Health Policy",
      "pos": [
        10759,
        10780
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The cluster health policy is used to evaluate cluster health state and node health states.",
      "pos": [
        10781,
        10871
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It can be defined in the cluster manifest.",
      "pos": [
        10872,
        10914
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If not present, it defaults to the default policy (0 tolerated failures).",
      "pos": [
        10915,
        10988
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Contains:",
      "pos": [
        10989,
        10998
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>ConsiderWarningAsError<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        11002,
        11029
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Specifies whether to treat Warning health reports as errors during health evaluation.",
      "pos": [
        11030,
        11115
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Default: False.",
      "pos": [
        11116,
        11131
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>MaxPercentUnhealthyApplications<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        11135,
        11171
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Maximum tolerated percentage of applications that can be unhealthy before the cluster is considered in Error.",
      "pos": [
        11172,
        11281
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>MaxPercentUnhealthyNodes<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        11285,
        11314
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Maximum tolerated percentage of nodes that can be unhealthy before the cluster is considered in Error.",
      "pos": [
        11315,
        11417
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In large clusters, there will always be nodes down or out for repairs, so this percentage should be configured to tolerate that.",
      "pos": [
        11418,
        11546
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following is an excerpt from a cluster manifest:",
      "pos": [
        11548,
        11600
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Application Health Policy",
      "pos": [
        11909,
        11934
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The application health policy describes how evaluation of events and children states aggregation is done for application and its children.",
      "pos": [
        11935,
        12073
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It can be defined in the application manifest, ApplicationManifest.xml in the application package.",
      "pos": [
        12074,
        12172
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If not specified, Service Fabric assumes the entity to be unhealthy if is has a health report or a child at Warning or Error health state.",
      "pos": [
        12173,
        12311
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The configurable policies are:",
      "pos": [
        12312,
        12342
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>ConsiderWarningAsError<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        12346,
        12373
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Specifies whether to treat Warning health reports as errors during health evaluation.",
      "pos": [
        12374,
        12459
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Default: False.",
      "pos": [
        12460,
        12475
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>MaxPercentUnhealthyDeployedApplications<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        12479,
        12523
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Maximum tolerated percentage of deployed applications that can be unhealthy before the application is considered in Error.",
      "pos": [
        12524,
        12646
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is calculated by dividing the number of unhealthy deployed applications over the number of nodes that the applications is currently deployed on in the cluster.",
      "pos": [
        12647,
        12811
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The computation rounds up to tolerate one failure on small number of nodes.",
      "pos": [
        12812,
        12887
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Default: 0%.",
      "pos": [
        12888,
        12900
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>DefaultServiceTypeHealthPolicy<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        12904,
        12939
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Specifies the default service type health policy, which will replace the default health policy for all service types in the application.",
      "pos": [
        12940,
        13076
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>ServiceTypeHealthPolicyMap<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        13080,
        13111
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Map with service health policies per service type, which replace the default service type health policy for the specified service types.",
      "pos": [
        13112,
        13248
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, in an application that contains a stateless Gateway service type and a stateful Engine service type, the health policy for the stateless and stateful service can be configured differently.",
      "pos": [
        13249,
        13450
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Specifying policy per service types allows a more granular control of the health of the service.",
      "pos": [
        13451,
        13547
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Service Type Health Policy",
      "pos": [
        13553,
        13579
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The service type health policy specifies how to evaluate and aggregate children of service.",
      "pos": [
        13580,
        13671
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Contains:",
      "pos": [
        13672,
        13681
      ]
    },
    {
